1300","1299":"1299","1310":"1310","1244":"1244","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Lavenham, Suffolk, England":"Lavenham, Suffolk, England","Moulsford, Berkshire, England":"Moulsford, Berkshire, England","Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England","Broughton, Buckinghamshire, England":"Broughton, Buckinghamshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cooke","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Cook  .","History: Francis Cooke (died 1663) and his eldest son John were passengers on the <i>Mayflower</i> in 1621; they were joined two years later by Francis's wife and other children. In the words of William Bradford, he lived long enough ‘to see his children's children have children’."],"variants":[{"name":"Cook","meanings":["English: occupational name for a cook, a seller of cooked meats, or a keeper of an eating house, from Middle English <i>cok</i>, <i>coke</i>, <i>cook</i>, <i>couk</i>, <i>cuk(e)</i> (Old English <i>cōc</i>) ‘cook’ or ‘seller of cooked foods’. See also   Kew  .","Irish and Scottish: usually identical in origin with the English name (see 1 above), but in some cases a shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Cúg</b> ‘son of Hugo’ (see   McCook  ).","Americanized form (translation into English) of various European surnames meaning ‘cook’, such as German and Jewish   Koch  , Dutch   Kook  , Polish <b>Kucharz</b> and   Kucharczyk  , Slovenian and Croatian   Kuhar  , North German   Kuk  ."]}]},{"name":"Johnathan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Respelling of   Jonathan  , as if a combination of   John   and   Nathan ."],"variants":[{"name":"Jonathan","meanings":["Biblical name, meaning ‘God has given’, composed of the same elements as those of   Matthew  , but in reverse order. This is the name of several characters in the Bible, most notably a son of King Saul, who was a devoted friend and supporter of the young David, even when David and Saul were themselves at loggerheads (1 Samuel 31; 2 Samuel 1:19–26). The name is often taken as symbolic of steadfast friendship and loyalty. Well-known bearers of the name include the Irish clergyman and writer  Jonathan Swift  (  1667-1745 ), British theatre director  Jonathan Miller  (  b. 1934 ), British actor  Jonathan Pryce  (  b. 1947 ), and British television presenter  Jonathan Ross  (  b. 1960 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":30,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Johnathan Cooke was born about 1260, in Broughton, Buckinghamshire, England, his father, Gary Lawrence Cooke, was 31 and his mother, Lady Stacie Kilpie, was 17. He married Jessica Hunsberger in 1299, in Lavenham, Suffolk, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died in 1310, in Moulsford, Berkshire, England, at the age of 51."},"et":{"about 1260–1310":"umbes 1260–1310","1260–1310":"1260–1310","1275–1345":"1275–1345","1260–1290":"1260–1290","1275–1310":"1275–1310","1300–1360":"1300–1360","1230–1275":"1230–1275","1244–1290":"1244–1290","about 1260":"umbes 1260","1275":"1275","1230":"1230","1360":"1360","1260":"1260","1 April 1300":"1. aprill 1300","1290":"1290","April 1300":"aprill 1300","1345":"1345","1300":"1300","1299":"1299","1310":"1310","1244":"1244","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Lavenham, Suffolk, England":"Lavenham, Suffolk, England","Moulsford, Berkshire, England":"Moulsford, Berkshire, England","Oxfordshire, England":"Oxfordshire, England","Broughton, Buckinghamshire, England":"Broughton, Buckinghamshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1260–1310":"noin 1260–1310","1260–1310":"1260–1310","1275–1345":"1275–1345","1260–1290":"1260–1290","1275–1310":"1275–1310","1300–1360":"1300–1360","1230–1275"